[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 outside China continues to grow and now totals 201. This includes 18 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 60 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 from the Southeast Asia region, 21 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 51 countries (including 16 territories) from the Americas region, and 41 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

The Americas region is reporting 20 485 new cases ( in the past 24 hours) of which 88.3% were reported by the USA, followed by Canada (3.6%) and Brazil (2.5%). The European region continues with rapid transmission, having confirmed 36 687 (58.2%) new cases and 2635 (79.6%) deaths in the 24 hours since the last WHO update, with Italy accounting for 16.3 % of newly confirmed cases, Spain for 22.3% of newly confirmed cases, Germany for 10.8% of newly confirmed cases, and France for 12.5% of newly confirmed cases (bringing the total of these 4 countries accounting for 62% of newly confirmed cases in Europe, down from 63.4% yesterday (28 Mar 2020). In the Eastern Mediterranean region, Iran reported 3076 new cases representing 80% of the regional newly reported cases. Pakistan and Saudi Arabia represent 7.6% and 2.6% respectively. In the African region, South Africa while representing 39.5% of total reported cases in the region, the newly reported cases in the past 24 hours only represented 9.8% of the regional total. Cote d'Ivoire represented 27.6% of newly reported cases in the region and Algeria 24.1%. In the Western Pacific region, Australia represents 27.2% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, with the Philippines representing 22.4% of the total (excluding China). In South East Asia, India reported 40.9% of newly confirmed cases followed by Thailand with 40.4% and Indonesia with 17.5%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases reported outside of China, by date of report and WHO region through [29 Mar 2020], at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and now the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA but other countries are following suit. Looking at the curve, it looks as though Europe may be leveling off in numbers of daily newly confirmed cases while the USA has accelerated markedly in the past 2 days.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: it is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have at times significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and, depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
